[27.6857, "o", "FINDING: HTTP/HTTPS Traffic Blocked by Overly Restrictive String Matching\r\n\r\nAFFECTED RULES:\r\n- Line 7: -A INPUT -p tcp --dport 80 -m string --string \"Mozilla\" --algo bm -j ACCEPT\r\n- Line 8: -A INPUT -p tcp --dport 443 -m string --string \"Mozilla\" --algo bm -j ACCEPT\r\n- Line 9: -A INPUT -p tcp --dport 80 -j DROP\r\n- Line 10: -A INPUT -p tcp --dport 443 -j DROP\r\n\r\nROOT CAUSE:\r\nThe iptables ruleset attempts to filter HTTP/HTTPS traffic by only accepting packets containing the string \"Mozilla\" in the packet payload. This appears to be an attempt at user-agent filtering or bot blocking. However, this approach has several critical issues:\r\n\r\n1. The string matching occurs at the packet level, not the HTTP header level\r\n2. It requires \"Mozilla\" to appear in the TCP payload of packets destined for ports 80/443\r\n3. Legitimate tools like curl (User-Agent: curl/x.x.x) don't contain \"Mozilla\" and are blocked\r\n4. The subsequent DROP rules (lines 9-10) catch all traffic that doesn't match the Mozilla string\r\n\r\nWHY SSH WORKS"]
[27.685781, "o", " BUT HTTP DOESN'T:\r\n- SSH (port 22): Has a simple ACCEPT rule with no string matching requirement (line 6)\r\n- HTTP/HTTPS (ports 80/443): Requires \"Mozilla\" string to be present in packet payload\r\n- When curl connects from 10.0.0.5, it sends \"curl/version\" as User-Agent, not \"Mozilla\"\r\n- The connection hangs because packets are being dropped by rules on lines 9-10\r\n\r\nRECOMMENDATION:\r\nThe string matching approach is fundamentally flawed for HTTP filtering because:\r\n- It operates at the wrong layer (packet vs application)\r\n- It blocks legitimate non-browser clients (curl, wget, APIs, monitoring tools)\r\n- It can be easily bypassed by including \"Mozilla\" in any packet payload\r\n- It doesn't actually validate proper HTTP User-Agent headers\r\n\r\nThe organization should either:\r\n1. Remove the string matching rules entirely and use proper application-layer filtering (WAF)\r\n2. Remove the DROP rules and rely on the default INPUT DROP policy\r\n3. Implement user-agent filtering at the web server level, not the firewall\r\n"]
